3.1 Preliminaries
Process of finding the intrinsic / extrinsic parameters
typically, a known calibration target is used
1. The known calibration target is captured in different poses
2. Features (e.g. corners) on the target are detected in the image
3. Camera intrinsics and extrinsics (poses) are jointly optimized
- poses has only 6 parameters, whereas the intrinsics have
from 5 to 10 parameters
- it is possible because we take much more observations
- non-linear optimization by minimizing reprojection error
e.g. checkerboard
Feature Detection & Description
In order to have a 3D reconstruction, we need to find
salient points that can be easily detect in other images
point features:
describe the appearance of local, salient regions
in an image
they describe and match images
taken from different viewpoints
requirements for point features:
- invariant to perspective and illumination
- same points should have similar vectors independent of pose/viewpoint
- RGB patches will not have this property, but..
Scale Invariant Frature Transform (SIFT)
- constructs a scale space, by iteratively filtering the image with
a Gaussian
- adjacent scales are subtracted, yielding Difference of Gaussian
interest points (blobs) are detected as extrema
this is also known as
blob detector
- SIFT rotates the descriptor to align with the domain gradient
orientation
- Gradient histograms are computed for local sub-regions of the
descriptor
- All histograms are concatenated and normalized to form a 128D
feature vector
- it was a seminal work thanks to its invariance
and robustness
- despite the great advancements, it is still used!
- ambiguous matches are typically filtered by
computing the ratio of distance from the closest
neighbor to the second closest.
A large ratio (>0.8) indicates that it may not be
the correct one
